<TEXT>
accused drug traffickers who turn 
themselves in to colombian authorities will not be extradited to 
the united states president cesar gaviria said wednesday in an 
official decree 
gaviria said the policy a notable departure from the past 
forms part of the governments plan to end drugrelated terrorism 
in colombia 
those who have been in crime and who have repented and who 
voluntarily turn themselves in to judges in order to freely confess 
their crimes may be tried by our judges based on our judicial 
order gaviria said in a nationwide televised speech 
during the past year the medellin cocaine cartel has been 
demanding an end to extradition the fate drug traffickers fear 
most 
the cartel in july declared a unilateral ceasefire in its 
terrorist attacks apparantly hoping that the new administration 
would end extraditions gaviria was inaugurated aug 7 
he said in his speech wednesday that criminals who turn 
themselves in will face lighter sentences 
judges will be given the capacity to reduce sentences of 
those who turn themselves in confess their crimes lay down 
weapons and other goods linked to their crimes and cooperate with 
investigations gaviria said 
in repeated communiques drug traffickers using the pseudonym 
the extraditables offered to turn themselves in to colombian 
judges in an apparant attempt to convince the government to end 
extraditions 
the extraditables communiques bore the letterhead we prefer 
a tomb in colombia to a jail cell in the united states 
gavirias predecessor virgilio barco reinitiated extraditions 
a year ago after drug traffickers declared war on the state 
twentytwo colombians accused of drug trafficking have been 
extradited to the united states since then 
violence meanwhile has soared with policemen in particular 
singled out as targets of hitmen hired by drug traffickers a 
domestic airliner in addition was blown out of the sky this year 
outside bogota killing more than 100 people 
the government has blamem the medellin cartel for killing more 
than 500 people including three presidential candidates 
thousands of others have died in fighting between rival drug 
gangs and violence by rightwing death squads financed by cocaine 
smugglers 
in his speech wednesday gaviria said three colombians currently 
awaiting extradition will be sent to the united states 
he said three other extradition requests by the united states 
have been rejected 
there are 14 people held in colombian jails awaiting extradition 
</TEXT>
