<TEXT>
the royal academy of arts in piccadilly opens an 
exhibition of 94 works by monet on friday hoping to draw at least 
a half million visitors over three months more than for any other 
show in its 222year history 
receipts at that level would bring in up to 56 million which 
could be used for its current huge renovation 
the works in the new exhibition monet in the 90s the series 
paintings are among the most beautiful and intriguing that monet 
did in his long life he was 86 when he died in 1926 at his home in 
giverny near paris 
in the 1890s he created series of paintings of the same 
subjects in different weather and light exhibiting each group as 
it was completed 
among the subjects in the show are 11 views of grainstacks 20 
of poplar trees 10 of rouen cathedral seven of misty mornings on 
the seine river 15 of the normandy coast four of the thames and 
five of the japanesestyle bridge over monets waterlily pond 
ten paintings of the creuse valley in central france include one 
loaned by britains queen mother elizabeth 
paul hayes tucker associate professor of art at the university 
of massachusetts spent four years assembling the exhibition from 
five continents and said monets paintings of the 1890s were 
perhaps the grandest incarnation of his art 
they have been collected from all over the world with immense 
difficulties and i believe we wont be able to see them together 
again in our lifetime said academy president roger de grey 
the show with some changes opened at boston museum of fine 
arts in february and was later seen at the art institute of 
chicago london is its only venue in europe 
in 1872 monets style was dubbed impressionism by a 
derisive critic who saw in paris his painting of le havre called 
impression sunrise 
monet subsequently became rich and famous as the father of 
impressionism the most popular art movement the world has ever 
known 
ironically the academy in 1871 turned down three monet 
paintings of london canvases of hyde park green park and the 
thames river at westminster 
the academy is the first gallery in britain to adopt the 
european and american system of selling tickets in advance and has 
already sold 16000 at 5 pounds 935 each 
the show is open daily through dec 9 
</TEXT>
