<TEXT>
a supermarket chain has slashed retail 
beef prices by as much as 50 percent and says its partly because 
the persian gulf crisis has cut off the iraqi market for irish meat 
superquinn which has 12 outlets in the greater dublin area has 
reduced the price of boneless rib steak from 320 to 170 per 
pound 
the whole thing is a cynical advertising ploy to grab a bit of 
the market william smith president of the irish master butchers 
association complained on tuesday he contended that wholesale 
prices had held steady 
there is an element of a special offer in it said fergal 
quinn owner of superquinn but he insisted it was a legitimate 
reaction to the gulf crisis 
its influenced by the fact that there is surplus of beef in 
the market place he said 
iraq had been a major buyer of irish beef but the market was 
cut off by a unordered trade embargo following iraqs invasion 
of kuwait on aug 2 
quinn added that the drop in demand was largely for hindquarter 
cuts and he had no plans to mark down the price of sirloin 
</TEXT>
