new york post management told its unions tuesday 
that the paper had to have a cost cutting plan by the end of next 
week and indicated the continued publication of the nations oldest 
daily was at stake 
post vice president and general manager richard t nasti said 
after a meeting with leaders of the papers 10 unions that the 
paper has set sept 15 as a deadline for reaching agreement he 
said he was optimistic the deadline will be met 
nasti didnt say specifically what would happen if the deadline 
werent met 
theodore kheel a labor mediator and unpaid adviser a union 
group who attended the meeting said he understood that management 
would suspend publication sept 15 if it couldnt reach agreement 
with the unions on 17 million in savings 
the papers 900 employees and 10 unions are represented by the 
allied printing trades council 
the councils president george mcdonald said management told 
us they are losing money and they are looking for some relief from 
the unions the losses have been blamed in part on the citys 
slumping economy 
publisher peter kalikow called the meeting and said through a 
spokesman the session was very cordial not a hostile meeting 
with both sides trying to work it out 
the post offered to open its books to its 10 unions and 
meetings with individual unions are scheduled throughout wednesday 
and thursday 
in a prepared statement nasti said management officials would 
meet with each union for lengthy and detailed explanations of 
their cost saving proposals 
this newspaper has served new york for 190 years and through a 
cooperative effort between labor and management it will continue to 
serve new york for another 190 years he said 
kalikow must find 25 million in annual savings to continue 
publishing the paper nasti said 
kheel said the 17 million figure is the amount the post hopes 
to save through costcutting measures affecting its unions with 
the rest to be made up in other ways 
kalikow took over the post from rupert murdoch in 1988 when the 
paper was losing about 3 million monthly concessions from the 
unions were part of the package that murdoch had to achieve in 
order to meet kalikows terms 
those same unions are now involved in intense negotiations with 
the rival daily news of new york the news is seeking contracts 
that would allow management to institute a variety of cost saving 
measures that the news says are critical to its survival 
