beginning oct 1 the start of fiscal year 1991 is still in 
effect officials said tuesday 
the die is cast and unless something is done the furlough 
will take place said spokesman jim greene of the departments 
food safety and inspection service 
last week the inspection agency notified the nations 6300 
federally inspected meat and poultry plants that the initial layoff 
order by president bush would be for a maximum of 36 hours during 
the oct 114 period 
agency administrator lester crawford said the layoffs would 
effectively shut down plants during the furlough periods 
the white house meanwhile said it is willing to listen to 
proposals for a budget reduction of less than 50 billion the 
current target under the grammrudman deficitreduction law 
budget negotiators will resume talks in private at andrews air 
force base md in hopes of reaching an agreement by sunday 
meanwhile if layoffs take effect on oct 1 as currently 
planned it could mean hardships for the industry and consumers 
said the american meat institute a trade association 
furloughs are not the answer said institute president j 
patrick boyle at best it would take years for the industry and 
the economy to recover the losses generated from furloughs of the 
magnitude being discussed for fiscal 1991 
the meat and poultry industry asked agriculture secretary 
clayton yeutter to find alternative methods of coping with the 
inspection agencys budget problems including the possibility of 
giving inspectors priority status so they could keep production 
lines moving 
