a new mechanical big foot with legs and feet 
instead of wheels is being developed to prowl forests the 
agriculture department says 
the vehicle will soon be strolling about the woods of 
southwest virginia near blacksburg home of virginia polytechnic 
institute and state university one of the machines developers 
the department said tuesday 
products technologist robert koeppen of the forest service said 
the machine could solve some forest management problems while 
helping protect forest ecosystems 
currently forest managers depend on rubbertired vehicles 
which can cause soil compaction rutting or damage to vegetation 
the agency said wheeled vehicles also are limited by terrain that 
is too rough steep wet or soft 
the machine called the robotic walking vehicle may 
alleviate such problems for example it can move sideways a 
maneuver koeppen said may help drastically reduce damage to forest 
soils and vegetation 
a public unveiling of the machine has been scheduled for sept 
11 at virginia tech with field tests to begin later this month 
the tests will include the machines performance on level 
mountainous and simulated lowlying wetland terrain 
