the 265th quartermaster detachment of the south 
carolina national guard is one of the reserve units called up for 
possible duty in saudi arabia national writer fred bayles is 
following the 14 guardsmen as they prepare for deployment overseas 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a silent semicircle of men stood in a 
room with dirt floors and unfinished walls at their center a 
candle heated a coffee can holding five tear gas tablets 
one by one as if in some initiation ceremony the men drank 
from hoses in cumbersome gas masks then took them off counted to 
10 spelled their last name and recited their social security 
numbers 
voices cracked halfway through the litany 
this mild torture suffered by the 14 members of the 265th 
quartermaster detachment is part of regular training for all us 
soldiers 
but for the water purification unit of the south carolina 
national guard the session in the posts gas chamber had added 
significance it marked the end of chemical warfare training meant 
to prepare the unit for mideast duty 
mobilized for deployment last week the allendale sc unit 
had spent four of six training days brushing up on nbc nuclear 
biological and chemical warfare 
the men heard lectures and watched movies about the effects of 
nerve agents choking gases and blister gas they walked in 
90degree heat wearing gas masks hoods overboots and bulky 
chemical warfare suits 
the gas chamber was a final stop to show the men their equipment 
worked 
with masks on the tear gas had little effect when masks came 
off the air in the dim room felt red hot as if the candles heat 
was everywhere the exposed faces went through escalating degrees 
of pain from the sensation of a slight sunburn to that of flayed 
flesh 
a quick walk into the outside breeze and a splash of water from 
a canteen cleared it away 
stings a little but it wasnt so bad said mark rooker at 
20 the youngest member of the unit 
to celebrate the 265ths graduation 2nd army commander lt gen 
james crysel came by the chamber 
crysel whose command includes the federalized 265th stood 
downwind from the chamber impervious to its fumes he spoke to 
several of the men about their unit and their families 
the men looking like mole people in their chemical warfare 
mufti gave muffled answers 
the 265ths men were assured all through training that the 
equipment can save their lives the bigger problem is functioning 
as a soldier in the claustrophobia of the mask and overgarments 
that quickly leave a man soaked through with sweat and smeared with 
the charcoal from the suits liner 
some people get an attitude in the mask said sgt van 
toliver a post instructor warned the group it makes you 
angry 
before the gas chamber session the men spent an hour in suits 
and masks practicing the frustrating task of swapping contaminated 
protective clothes for fresh ones 
when the sweatdrenched men finally removed their masks the 
anger sgt toliver warned of was obvious 
they throw gas at us when were over there and were going to 
die said ulysses calhoun one of the units younger members 
might as well take off the mask and get it over with 
not everyone agreed 
ill stay with the mask said sgt hullie cohen a guardsman 
for 16 years i plan to do what i can to survive 
cohen a burly 40yearold brick mason often breaks a moment of 
tension with a joke he is equally deliberate on the basketball 
court choosing his shots while the units younger members gun for 
impossible baskets it seems he rarely misses 
it was cohens first time in the gas chamber he was one of the 
few who volunteered to go through again this time without a mask 
i just wanted to see what i could stand he said the gas 
temporarily blinded him he had to be led out 
