<TEXT>
an effort is under way to get people in the 
iron city to stop eating like steelworkers 
the state has joined 100 companies and two drug store chains in 
sponsoring the pittsburgh community health challenge which will 
offer some 52000 workers and other members of the public a 10week 
analysis of their eating habits 
organizers hope to turn people away from an arteryclogging 
legacy of pirogies kielbasa gyros and other highfat ethnic 
dishes that sustained generations of robust steelworkers 
our parents developed highfat kinds of foods when they were 
working in the steel mills said donna donati the programs 
executive director they used to work very hard burn those 
calories off 
but were eating the same foods they ate when they hung their 
clothes outside on the line rather than what we do sitting around 
as they dry in the dryer 
the city once dependent on steel has created service 
hightech and medical jobs since the decline of the mills in the 
early 1980s 
supporters of the program dined on lowfat quiche and cheesecake 
at a tuesday lunch to unveil the effort aimed at curbing the citys 
appetite for foods loaded with saturated fats and cholesterol both 
linked to heart disease 
questionnaires about family medical history smoking exercise 
and diet will be handed out the participating companies including 
ppg industries inc hj heinz co and allegheny ludlum corp 
among the areas largest employers 
thrift drugs and legend pharmacies will distribute 
questionnaires at their stores 
a computer analysis will tell respondents how they compare to 
average americans in the risk of heart disease 
its really personal it will hit them right on the head 
ms donati said 
pennsylvania had 2668 heart disease deaths per 100000 people 
in 1986 the most recent year available said dr lewis kuller of 
the university of pittsburghs school of public health the 
national average was 2468 deaths per 100000 
most southwestern pennsylvania residents are ignorant of the 
dangers of cholesterol and fat researchers said 
most of them dont have the foggiest idea what theyre doing 
to themselves kuller said its so simple too people can 
reduce cholesterol in their food through simple changes and 
