<TEXT>
britains middle east empire is long gone but 
londons strong political and defense ties in the region have given 
it a highprofile role in the persian gulf crisis 
britain helped draw the current map of the middle east after 
world war i and was deeply involved in governing many countries in 
the region including both iraq and kuwait 
last month it was the first power to send weapons in support of 
the us buildup in the region and last weekend prime minister 
margaret thatcher bore the brunt of iraqi invective over the wests 
military challenge to its invasion of kuwait 
mrs thatcher accused president saddam hussein of iraq of having 
hidden behind the skirts of women and children and the iraqi 
news agency denounced her as an old hag 
thatcher would do well to bear in mind that the empire on 
whose possessions the sun did not go down has long been defunct 
and neither she nor any of her allies will be able to set the clock 
back it said 
dr basim musallam director of the center of mideast studies at 
cambridge university says the historical background has made 
britains role in the persian gulf bigger than the number of 
planes it has sent 
britain sells sophisticated military hardware to the gulf 
states and british officers help train their soldiers and pilots 
in 1988 britain signed its biggest arms deal ever to sell 
saudi arabia nearly 20 billion worth of warplanes 
britain was the last imperial power to withdraw from the 
gulf musallam said in an interview the british know the 
terrain very well they have close connections with the local 
rulers much more than the french or americans 
originally britain needed the middle east to shut out russia and 
germany and secure its routes to the orient and it ruled arabia 
from india until after world war i 
the seven sheikdoms which now comprise the united arab emirates 
and kuwait gave britain control of foreign affairs and defense in 
the late 19th century bahrain was a british protectorate from 1861 
until 1971 
a romantic angloarab tradition developed personified by such 
figures as lawrence of arabia 
oil changed britains interest in the middle east the royal 
navy switched to oil in 1912 just as the anglopersian oil company 
which is now british petroleum started operations in persia now 
iran 
having defeated the ottoman empire in world war i britain and 
france drew new mideast boundaries france got lebanon and syria 
britain got iraq transjordan now jordan and palestine 
britain installed friendly arab rulers who were more or less 
amenable to british protection a situation which survived more or 
less until the late 1930s according to oxford university 
historian alastair parker 
then came more changes oil was struck in saudi arabia and the 
americans moved into the middle east for the first time meanwhile 
the jews were demanding a state in palestine 
britain was torn and in 1939 it opted for a proarab policy 
after world war ii the british empire began to wane but 
londons interests in the middle east remained paramount in 1956 
it joined france in trying to seize the suez canal from the 
egyptian nationalist leader gamal abdel nasser in the early 1960s 
it sent troops to ward off threats in the persian gulf and adan in 
presentday yemen 
prof john vincent a middle east historian at the university of 
bristol says iraq shouldnt be surprised by britains response to 
the kuwait invasion we are sticking to precedent he said in 
an interview this is what weve always done 
our interest has stayed the same down the ages he said 
we want a balanced strong independent middle east which isnt 
under the thumb of any great powers and which isnt under a 
regional dictator 
columnist robert harris mused in the sunday times at the 
reversal in us and british roles 
for half a century after world war i american foreign policy 
was dominated by a desire to break up the british empire that 
policy succeeded perhaps too well he wrote 
now as washingtons gunboats are required to steam along our 
old imperial routes to the gulf one cannot help but smile 
</TEXT>
