<TEXT>
federal scientists have concluded a controversial 
bloodheating treatment for aids did nothing to help two us 
patients 
the team of researchers from the national institute of allergy 
and infectious diseases also said the hyperthermia treatment a 
technique to raise body temperature and kill the aids virus should 
not be repeated 
dr kenneth alonso who helped pioneer the technique charged 
that the report was replete with errors and merely an attempt 
to discredit his work 
apparently any work which does not fit your thesis is 
ignored alonso said in a letter to dr lawrence deyton niaid 
assistant director for community and head of the investigative 
team the letter was released on tuesday 
a summary of the investigative teams findings released tuesday 
by the niaid said hyperthermia as applied in these cases 
appears to have offered no clinical immunologic or virologic 
benefits to these two patients 
niaid reported that the two patients still were infected by the 
aids virus 
there does not appear any support for further human 
experimentation in this area at this time the summary concluded 
the institutes report is the harshest official criticism yet of 
the treatment which offered hope to thousands of aids sufferers 
earlier this year after one patient pronounced himself cured 
niaid researchers visited alonso at his request july 25 to learn 
about his technique which had been performed in the united states 
on two patients infected with the virus a third man reportedly a 
very ill aids patient from new york received the treatment from 
alonso in mexico and died hours later 
the first patient 33yearold carl crawford reported dramatic 
improvements in his kaposis sarcoma a skin cancer afflicting many 
aids patients he went so far as to tell reporters he had been 
cured of aids 
but tests showed no evidence the man had kaposis sarcoma the 
niaid reported the researchers suggested crawfords skin problems 
resulted from an infection from cat scratches that was cleared up 
by antibiotics 
alonso called that conclusion absurd 
the second patient a 38yearold with advanced aids whose 
identity was kept confidential reported little or no improvement 
after hyperthermia according to the niaid report alonso disputed 
those findings as well 
hyperthermia commonly used to treat infections before the 
advent of antibiotics is still used against some cancers 
in the procedure developed by alonso and his former partner dr 
william logan the patients blood was run through a heater and 
back into the body to raise body temperature 
the niaid report however noted that some researchers have 
reported that heat can actually increase the aids virus 
