intelsat the international satellite consortium 
is suing titan rocket builder martin marietta corp for 400 
million over the botched launch of a 145 million communications 
satellite now stuck in a useless orbit 
in the lawsuit filed tuesday in federal court in baltimore 
intelsat charged that martin marietta miswired the rocket then 
gave false assurances of its quality before the march 14 launch 
for which intelsat paid 115 million 
martin marietta has said a wiring problem caused failure of the 
satellite and its attached booster rocket to separate from the 
titan when they reached orbit 
as a result the uninsured satellite fell short of its station 
22300 miles above earth and will be a total loss unless it gets a 
boost a shuttle crew will try to rescue it next year at a cost to 
intelsat of about 90 million 
intelsat claimed martin marietta didnt take proper steps to 
detect the flaw and failed to properly analyze test data or 
supervise crews that built the rocket 
elliott miller martin marietta director of corporate relations 
said the lawsuit had no merit and that intelsat had declined to buy 
insurance 
under the launch services contract between martin marietta and 
intelsat the relationship of the parties for risk of loss is 
clearly set forth he said the contract provides that martin 
marietta is not liable for the satellite failure to achieve orbit 
martin marietta based in bethesda md built the rocket near 
denver 
the aerospace company attempted a preemptive strike against 
intelsat in july asking the federal court to declare that its only 
legal responsibility was to provide a replacement launch martin 
marietta said it might have to go out of the commercial launch 
business if it were made to pay damages 
but in its lawsuit intelsat noted that martin marietta was 
considering dropping out anyway 
