<TEXT>
a federal prosecutor warned jurors today they 
would enter a strange world during the trial of an excia agent 
accused of not paying taxes on his share of irancontra arms 
profits and hiding some of it in switzerland 
the evidence will take you into a world you are unfamiliar 
with stuart e abrams told jurors in opening arguments its a 
world of international arms deals secret financial accounts and a 
world in which financial transactions are made in large sums of 
money 
thomas g clines 62 of middleburg va is on trial for 
allegedly underreporting arms sale earnings on his 1985 and 1986 
tax returns he also is charged with failing to tell the internal 
revenue service about overseas bank accounts 
clines and others allegedly sold arms to iran then used some of 
the profits to supply weapons to the contra rebels in nicaragua at 
a time when such aid was banned by congress some of the money was 
kept in a foreign account codenamed ctea according to the 
congressional irancontra report issued in november 1987 
the government contends clines reaped about 882000 in 
commissions 
clines pleaded innocent march 9 to all four counts of an 
indictment returned feb 22 if convicted of all crimes he could 
be fined up to 1 million and sentenced to 16 years in prison 
clines reported gross receipts of 265000 for the tax year 1985 
and 402513 for 1986 prosecutors said 
abrams told jurors that clines received 20 percent of arms sales 
profits in 1985 and 30 percent in 1986 
some of the money he sent back to banks in the united states 
but not all of it abrams said hundreds of thousands of dollars 
were transferred into the swiss account he said 
defense attorney paula m junghans told the jurors in her 
opening statements that clines is looking forward to the 
opportunity to explain his side 
dont assume because the government has amassed all this 
paperwork that something must be wrong she told the jurors 
there is no charge in this case that says it is a crime to buy 
and sell arms 
retired air force maj gen richard v secord is expected to be 
the first government witness 
secord enlisted clines a 29year cia agentturnedinvestor and 
consultant as the primary broker for the arms deals in 1985 and 
1986 according to the congressional report 
secord and iranianborn businessman albert hakim operated the 
enterprise a maze of companies set up to carry out the arms 
sales to iran and the military supply shipments to the contras 
prosecutors said the enterprise was formed at the request of 
former national security adviser john poindexter and oliver north 
a retired marine lieutenant colonel who was a national security 
council staff member 
the enterprise took in nearly 48 million 122 million more 
than its expenditures during its first two years of operation 
the congressional report said secord hakim and clines took 
commissions from the 122 million surplus to reward themselves 
for their work on arms deliveries the report said the 
commissions totaled approximately 44 million 
prosecutors have alleged that secord made more than 1 million 
from his role while secord has maintained that he made no more 
than 250000 
secord pleaded guilty nov 8 1989 to one felony count of 
making false statements to the irancontra congressional 
committees he was sentenced in january to two years of probation 
