sept 3 
the guardian london on the persian gulf 
because america is the greatest democracy it cannot adequately 
play the part of freedoms flying squad 
the bitter ghosts of the vietnam venture are not exorcized they 
are one of the dominant themes of hollywood at the start of the 
90s the controlled experiments of grenada and panama sanitized 
war with no bodies in the bag for the cameras have not 
reconciled the american voter the human being with human rights 
to a world where thousands upon thousands of lives may be put in 
jeopardy in foreign fields 
the myth of a hightech war fought by fighting machines at long 
range is just that a myth the mirror image of a television world 
which showed the citizens of the soviet union what economic misery 
they were enduring is that those same screens will show dead 
americans and dead civilians caught up in a melee of bloodshed 
there is no longterm reality to this role it is not what 
democracies are about it is an attempt by old minds left bereft 
by the crumbling of the cold war to construct a new order which 
merely echoes the simplicities of the past 
in fact there is only one global policeman that for its 
frailties is the united nations because it represents the 
collective wisdom of a world of many nations and infinite systems 
of government it is not the excuse for action in the gulf it is 
for good or ill the pivot of it 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
sept 3 
straits times singapore on the soviet union 
it is getting increasingly difficult these days to fault soviet 
president mikhail gorbachev for radicalism the man who began his 
career at the kremlin as an undoubted revolutionary though of the 
peaceful variety shows signs five years later of transformation 
into an establishment figure who lives an uneasy life between the 
nostalgia of revolution and the realities of power 
he acknowledged last week that there was public scepticism over 
the reform program an economic collapse of the country could not 
be ruled out as could not serious tears in its political fabric 
 
if his reforms are to mean anything they must not only move 
forward but gather momentum an honest and speedy transition to a 
market economy is a necessity not a luxury 
gorbachev can take heart that there is someone who understands 
just how critical matters are russian federation president boris 
yeltsin whose radical posture calls for privatization the closing 
of inefficient industries and an end to heavy subsidies has often 
differed with gorbachev 
it was reported however that the two had agreed last week on 
the need for urgent and drastic action that cooperation will 
hopefully come about and continue the kremlin leader needs all the 
radicals he can get to put the spirit back into the gorbachev 
revolution in present soviet circumstances nothing less than a 
revolution is needed to keep reform alive 
</TEXT>
