<TEXT>
the eightyear battle over the salt 
caves hydroelectric project is a western showdown reminiscent of 
those between freerange cattlemen and fencebuilding homesteaders 
but this fight is between a coalition of a city developers a 
local congressman and a federal agency facing an alliance of state 
agencies voters outoftown congressmen fishermen and 
environmentalists 
at issue is an 11mile stretch of the klamath river 27 miles 
southwest of klamath falls in southcentral oregon 
initial proposals by the city of klamath falls would have 
drowned the river behind a dam but the proposal now is for no dam 
at all just a series of canals and conduits bringing water from 
an existing dam upstream that hasnt lessened opposition 
the proposal now rests in two sets of hands 
the federal energy regulatory commission could sweep aside 
most of the objections raised by state agencies simply by granting 
a license 
congress is considering a bill that would block the commission 
by including the upper klamath river in the federal wild and scenic 
river system 
if the agency is going to crush state and regional decisions 
we think that is another reason wild and scenic legislation should 
be passed to protect this river and protect the broad range of 
people opposed to this project said chris orsinger spokesman 
for the oregon rivers council an environmental group 
opponents say the project would destroy the last freeflowing 
troutfilled stretch of a waterway already shackled by four dams 
supporters say the project can generate millions of dollars to 
help klamath falls get back on its feet after a decade of decline 
no customers have yet agreed to buy the dams electricity and 
opponents say the project cant make a profit 
the federal energy commission says there is a need for the 
electricity and the project can make a profit estimated by the 
city at 3 million a year 
in 1985 klamath falls applied to the commission for a permit to 
build a 117 million 130foottall dam at salt cave a spot named 
for holes in a cliff that would generate 140 megawatts of 
electricity 
the city even swung a deal that so far has financed planning and 
design without costing taxpayers a dime it sold 250 million worth 
of bonds then reinvested the money at a higher interest rate than 
it had to pay on the bonds 
the oregon department of fish and wildlife protested that the 
original proposal would flood one of the states premier trout 
streams and rafters said it would dry up a top summer whitewater 
run 
the city scaled down the dam in 1986 and tacked on a ski area 
to mitigate for the loss of fishing and rafting 
in 1987 thengov neil goldschmidt said oregons environment 
should be enjoyed by all not sacrificed to economic development 
for one city 
the state department of environmental quality denied the project 
a crucial water quality permit the state department of energy 
questioned the need for the power 
and reps peter defazio ron wyden and les aucoin all 
democrats from western oregon across the cascades from klamath 
falls introduced the first bill to grant federal protection to the 
river the bill failed 
in 1988 the quasigovernmental northwest power planning council 
created by congress to plan for power needs in the northwest 
included the upper klamath river among 40000 miles of northwest 
waterways where it did not want hydroelectric development 
oregon voters approved an initiative putting the upper klamath 
on the state scenic waterways list 
last year the federal energy commission suggested doing away 
with the dam and the reservoir and klamath falls agreed 
the new design would draw water directly from the tailrace of 
the jc boyle dam carry it 10 miles downstream through canals and 
conduits built into the canyon wall to a powerhouse where it would 
spin generators and be returned to the river 
michael hartfield spokesman for the salt caves project says 
the nodam proposal would improve trout habitat by taking away the 
periodic surges of water released from the boyle dam leaving a 
constant flow 
but that would mean less water in the river say opponents who 
also object to the canals and conduits 
a us supreme court decision this year backed the citys claim 
that a federal energy commission license would override the states 
opposition 
in the meantime defazio wyden and aucoin introduced another 
bill for federal protection 
the federal agency has said it will await the bills fate in 
congress before acting 
its up to congress said orsinger 
