<TEXT>
doctors should encourage their patients to write 
down their wishes about whether they want lifesustaining treatment 
stopped if they become hopelessly ill according to a group medical 
ethicists 
the living wills spell out what kind of care people want if 
they become too sick to speak for themselves such directives are 
required in two states new york and missouri before food water 
and medical treatment can be withdrawn 
in june the us supreme court upheld missouris guidelines 
writing that states can require clear and convincing evidence 
of a patients wishes 
the patient in that case nancy cruzan had been in a vegetative 
state since a 1983 car accident her parents believed she would not 
want to be kept alive in such a condition and sought to have her 
tube feeding stopped however she had not made a living will and 
the court refused to allow her parents to speak for her 
a statement on the case was drawn up at the annual conference of 
bioethicists in lutsen minn in july signed by 36 ethicists and 
published in thursdays new england journal of medicine 
besides urging doctors to learn what their patients want they 
wrote that physicians should also encourage patients to discuss 
their preferences with their families and close friends and to 
prepare and sign advance directives 
even though unnecessary in most states such statements often 
help to resolve legally and ethically troubling cases they noted 
they added that the supreme court decision does not change the 
laws ethical standards and medical practices that have evolved 
since the karen ann quinlan case in 1976 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

