three radical leftists will plead guilty to 
setting off bombs at the us capitol and seven other sites and 
the government has agreed to drop charges against three other 
people 
laura j whitehorn linda s evans and marilyn j buck are 
scheduled to plead guilty friday in us district court here to 
participating in a conspiracy to set off the eight bombs that 
damaged property but caused no injuries according to court papers 
filed last week in federal court 
the nov 7 1983 blast at the capitol blew a hole in a wall 
outside the senate chambers damaging five paintings and knocking 
the door to democratic leader robert byrds office off its hinges 
as part of the deal government prosecutors agreed to drop 
bombing charges against three other members of the leftist group 
who are serving lengthy prison sentences for possession of 
explosives 
the six defendants are members of a radical group that variously 
identified itself as the armed resistance unit the revolutionary 
fighting group and the red guerrilla resistance unit 
the group is linked to the 16 million armed robbery of a 
