participating in the brinks holdup and four other armed robberies 
the plea agreement filed by us attorney jay b stephens said 
the disposition of the bombing case was in the interest of 
justice but gave no reason for why the government agreed to 
settle the case 
lawyers familiar with the case said a may supreme court decision 
in a new york case on the issue of double jeopardy figured in the 
governments willingness to drop the charges against susan l 
rosenberg timothy a blunk and alan berkman 
rosenberg and blunk are serving 58year sentences for possessing 
more than 600 pounds of explosives they were caught loading the 
explosives into a rented storage bin in cherry hill nj in 1984 
berkman a physician is serving a 10year term for possession 
of explosives weapons and false identify cards when he was 
arrested in 1985 in doylestown pa 
a seventh defendant in the case elizabeth duke is a fugitive 
in 1989 us district judge harold h greene dismissed the 
bombing charges against rosenberg blunk and berkman ruling that 
the evidence in the case had already been used to convict them of 
the earlier firearms charges 
the us district court of appeals for the district of columbia 
reinstated the charges saying the new indictment did not violate 
the rules against double jeopardy 
but the defense renewed its doublejeopardy claims last spring 
after the supreme court said in a new york case that prosecutors 
cannot bring charges based on evidence that had already been used 
to convict the defendant of a different offense 
greene has not ruled on that motion 
