<TEXT>
an international commission found wednesday that 
the soviet government issued misleading statements on the fate of 
raoul wallenberg the swedish diplomat credited with saving tens of 
thousands of hungarian jews from the nazis during world war ii 
wallenberg vanished after the soviets arrested him in budapest 
in 1945 in the wars final days on allegations he spied for 
germany moscow later said he had died 
wallenbergs relatives say they received reports he is alive 
under detention in the soviet union he would now be 77 
the 25member private commission composed of soviet swedish 
us and canadian members said its investigation of the conduct of 
soviet authorities in the case brings into question their moral 
standing in the matter 
wallenberg a member of a prominent family of bankers and 
industrialists repeatedly risked his life by hiding jews in houses 
he bought or rented often with his own money shortly before 
budapest was liberated he persuaded the nazis to cancel a plan to 
kill 70000 jews still living in the citys ghetto 
in 1981 the united states made wallenberg an honorary citizen 
swedish authorities presented the kremlin with witnesses 
reports in the 1950s and 1960s that wallenberg was alive and was 
seen by nonsoviets at vladimir prison 12 miles outside moscow 
the soviets responded with the gromyko memorandum of feb 6 
1957 saying they investigated reports from vladimir prison and 
concluded wallenberg died of a heart attack in moscows lubyanka 
prison in 1947 
this year the soviets opened some archives to foreign 
investigators for the first time and let the commission hold 
interviews and search files at vladimir prison 
we have found that the soviet union never conducted any 
investigation at vladimir prison said the report issued at a 
news conference by the newly formed sovietinternational joint 
commission on the fate and whereabouts of raoul wallenberg 
it found that despite soviet claims of having investigated the 
case prison archives were not examined prison officials were 
not interviewed and witnesses whose testimony was relevant were 
not examined 
this finding is particularly disturbing and painful as the 
soviet union continued to receive testimony from the swedish 
government in the 1950s based largely on witness testimony from 
imprisoned foreign nationals at vladimir prison who had left the 
soviet union that raoul wallenberg was alive in the 1950s 
yet for 12 years from 194557 the soviet union insisted that 
raoul wallenberg is not in the soviet union and he is not known to 
us 
quoting from the gromyko memorandum named after the late soviet 
foreign minister andrei a gromyko kremlin authorities looked into 
the matter and could not find any information whatsoever about 
wallenberg being in the soviet union none of those 
interrogated knew anything about wallenberg 
accordingly the commissions finding that no investigation had 
ever been conducted by the soviet union at vladimir prison not only 
discredits the gromyko memorandum and the soviet position that 
wallenberg died in 1947 but brings into question their moral 
standing to make any claim whatever in the absence of any 
investigation by them it said 
the commission also found that the kgb secret police kept its 
own files on incarcerated foreigners 
accordingly the commission finds it rather incredulous that 
the kgb claimed to have discovered by accident in october 1989 
items belonging to raoul wallenberg prison registration card 
passport money personal belongings and which it turned over to 
the wallenberg family during their visit 
indeed the former director of archives at vladimir 
found this kgb claim to be rather ludicrous 
moreover the kgb had previously claimed for 32 years that it 
had no information or materials whatsoever relating to raoul 
wallenberg 
members of the commission include wallenbergs brother guy von 
dardel of sweden irwin cotler of canada marvin w markinen an 
american professor who formerly was incarcerated at vladimir 
prison cronid lubarsky another former vladmir inmate and rolf 
bjornerstedt a former united nations assistant secretary it also 
included five soviets 
</TEXT>
