<TEXT>
lord caradon the former british permanent 
representative to the united nations died wednesday in a plymouth 
nursing home caradon was 82 said his son paul foot 
no cause of death was given for caradon who spent more than 30 
years in britains former colonial office and helped four colonies 
gain independence 
he was not afraid to differ with the governments he served and 
once resigned rather than defend a policy he did not support 
caradon was born hugh foot on oct 8 1907 the son of a 
distinguished political family 
his brother michael was leader of the labor party opposition 
from 1980 to 1983 and remains a labor member of parliament 
caradon was educated at leighton park a quaker school at 
reading and at cambridge university he was president of the 
cambridge union a student body in 1929 
later that year he entered the old colonial office which was 
responsible for administering britains colonies 
in 1943 he was appointed colonial secretary in cyprus acting 
as governor in 1944 
the next 13 years he held a variety of colonial office posts 
including the chief secretary in nigeria and governorinchief of 
jamaica he was knighted in 1951 
from 195760 caradon was governor and commanderinchief in 
cyprus 
he is credited with bringing the rival greek and turkish leaders 
together and he left the island having completed his mission to 
forge a new independent republic 
a government citation praises his wisdom courage and 
humanity and his unwearying efforts in the cyprus negotiations 
in 1961 caradon went to the united nations as british 
representative on the trusteeship council but he did not agree 
with what he considered the british governments lenient attitude 
toward the white minority in the colony of rhodesia and resigned 
rather than speak for a policy he did not support 
in 1963 he was appointed consultant to the un special fund 
dealing with the governments of newly independent countries on 
matters of economic development 
the british government made him a life peer in 1964 and sent him 
to the united nations as permanent representative a post he held 
until 1970 
during this time he gathered support for sanctions against ian 
smiths rhodesia after smith made his unilateral declaration of 
independence he also served on the un expert group on south 
africa 
he retired in 1970 but continued with some of his united 
nations activities becoming a consultant on the un development 
programme 
in a television interview caradon admitted he never smiled when 
journalists were nearby 
it was one of the first lessons i learned in the diplomatic 
service he confided you never know when there may be a stray 
photographer near and in the newspapers the next morning alongside 
the headlines saying 100000 people dead there is a picture of 
you smiling all over your face 
caradon married florence tod in 1936 she died in 1985 he is 
survived by three sons and a daughter 
funeral arrangements were incomplete 
</TEXT>
