refused to comment on his interrogation by investigators tuesday 
israeli reports said wednesday police also suspected deri had 
advance knowledge about gilats being wiretapped deri has not 
commented 
deris supporters seek to use the tapes as a possible way to 
exonerate him some israeli reports said the recordings contained 
conversations between gilat and turner coordinating their moves 
the issue led to radio discussions by religious experts on what 
jewish law has to say about admitting a wiretap as evidence 
some rabbis argued that 13thcentury sage gershon ben solomon of 
arles france ordered a man punished for reading someone elses 
mail without consent the same principle could be applied to a 
wiretap they reasoned 
rabbi ovadiah yosef of shas a former chief sephardic rabbi 
said nobody could hide his words or deeds from god 
the almighty has a tape with television pictures he was 
quoted as telling followers nobody can go to heaven and claim to 
the creator i never said such things 
deris supporters demand the tapes be declared legal evidence 
and that turner be ousted if found to be in the wrong 
gilat won a supreme court injunction monday barring use of the 
tapes 
