<TEXT>
a federal judge on wednesday rejected an attempt 
to block an execution by a drugdispensing machine that prisoners 
lawyers contend could inflict cruel and unusual punishment 
us district judge james zagel denied an injunction to block 
the sept 12 execution of charles walker who could become the 
first person executed in illinois in 28 years 
zagel said the convicted murderer shouldnt become a pawn in 
a fight over the states death penalty statute 
lawyers working on behalf of condemned prisoners had filed a 
lawsuit in federal court seeking classaction status for the nearly 
130 illinois inmates on death row 
the lawsuit contended the state would violate its own death 
penalty law by executing the inmates with a machine that delivers a 
lethal combination of three drugs state law specifically states 
that two drugs are to be used 
the judge continued the hearing on the lethalinjection issue 
for eight weeks which would be after walkers execution date 
the lawsuit recalls the controversy in florida over whether its 
electric chair was a valid means of execution or a torture device 
during a may 4 execution of jesse joseph tafero flames and 
sparks shot from the inmates head and smoke filled floridas 
execution chamber tafero was finally declared dead after three 
jolts of electricity 
attorneys for three condemned inmates won indefinite stays from 
the 11th us circuit court of appeals in atlanta with arguments 
the electric chair was not functioning properly their status was 
unclear after a successful execution in the same electric chair in 
july 
the lawyers in illinois requested an immediate injunction 
blocking all state executions until their dispute was settled 
there hasnt been an execution in illinois since 1962 
stuart altschuler a lawyer for the plaintiffs said the lawsuit 
was filed because the states lethal injection machine execution 
procedures and personnel are suspect under state law 
the law amended in 1983 to provide for execution by lethal 
injection rather than electrocution specifies that two chemicals 
be used an ultrashort acting barbiturate to sedated the 
condemned person and a drug that causes paralysis 
but the machine injects three chemicals into the body sodium 
pentathol a barbiturate to render prisoner unconscious 
pancuronium bromide which paralyzes the prisoner and potassium 
chloride which stops the prisoners heart 
it is the potassium chloride that lawyers find objectionable 
they say it is an electrolyte that could cause an excruciating 
burning sensation in the prisoners vein and since he would be 
paralyzed by the second drug he would be unable tell anyone 
an inmate put to death on the machine could vomit and suffocate 
which constitutes cruel and unusual punishment in violation of 
plaintiffs rights under the eighth amendment the lawsuit 
contends 
we have not asked the judge in any way to invalidate the death 
penalty he said weve merely asked that the state adhere to 
its own laws 
altschuler said he planned to file an immediate appeal 
terry madsen chief of the illinois attorney generals criminal 
appeals division said the state continues to test its lethal 
injection machine many other states have used it properly he 
added 
madsen said he was confident the machine would not inflict any 
pain upon walker or others 
but fred leuchter jr the boston man who invented the 25000 
machine that illinois will use said last month he tested the 
machine in may and found it failed 70 percent of the time 
leuchter said the machine is very likely to fail during 
walkers execution because the machinery had been sitting in a damp 
place since it was bought in 1987 
state prison officials however said leuchter made the comments 
out of spite after they dropped him as a consultant to the 
execution 
zagel also denied the lawsuit classaction status saying such a 
method should be used only in cases where the plaintiffs arent 
readily identifiable 
he scheduled a hearing for oct 31 to examine how the states 
lethal injection machine functions and for a briefing on the 
remaining plaintiffs convicted killers charles silagy and walter 
stewart both are on death row 
zagel said he felt no need to act quickly since no execution 
date has been set for either man and since he ordered walker 
excluded from the lawsuit 
in denying the petition to block walkers execution the judge 
noted that walker has repeatedly indicated he wants to die to pay 
his debt to society for the 1983 slayings of a man and a woman in 
southern illinois 
</TEXT>
