<TEXT>
president mengistu haile mariam 
beams and waves to the masses from a huge billboard in addis 
ababas main square 
beneath it a uniformed security guard uses a stick to control 
the hundreds of ethiopians who besiege the immigration department 
every day for exit visas 
one of them the wife of a ranking politician shares a 
whispered joke with a visitor we like to think hes waving 
goodbye 
mengistu who gained power after a military coup toppled emperor 
haile selassie in 1974 seems determined to hang on despite 
military diplomatic and economic setbacks 
consider his problems 
two major guerrilla armies have demoralized a military made up 
largely of forcibly enlisted youngsters with little training and 
less inclination to fight for mengistu 
after nearly three decades of war secessionist rebels occupy 
nearly all of eritrea the northernmost province a smaller allied 
force holds neighboring tigre province and has swept southward to 
within 100 miles of the capital 
the soviet union for 13 years ethiopias ally and arms 
supplier has withdrawn most of its military advisers has reduced 
weapons shipments and recommends negotiations to settle ethiopias 
internal conflicts cuban advisers also have left 
ethiopia says the military absorbs half its annual budget the 
economy is in tatters the arms debt to the soviet union is 
estimated at 5 billion to 6 billion and moscow indicates it 
expects to be paid western nations and international lending 
agencies to which ethiopia owes an additional 2 billion to 3 
billion also expect payment 
famine is an almost constant threat particularly in the 
north where drought and war have limited harvests for years more 
than 1 million people died in the last great famine in 198485 
and only continuing relief efforts have prevented a repetition 
anywhere else in the world a leader confronted with such a 
litany of disasters would have bowed out but our man will brave it 
out said an ethiopian political scientist 
how long mengistu can do so may depend on eritrea nearly a 
third of his 315800man army is under siege in the eritrean 
capital asmara surrounded by rebels of the eritrean peoples 
liberation front 
mengistu has acknowledged the fall of asmara could bring down 
his government diplomats in addis ababa say he is determined to 
hold the provincial capital 
dawit wolde giorgis a former ethiopian official who headed the 
relief program in the 198485 famine and now lives in new jersey 
said mengistu has lost control of the country but still 
prevails in the capital primarily because the opposition 
movements are disunited 
there is no real source of strength in the regime except the 
machinery of terror and need for economic survival he said 
perhaps 100000 people in the establishment are loyal to him 
because they know that their life and security depend on the 
survival of mengistu 
goshu wolde a former foreign minister now living in maryland 
said the army could dislodge mengistu but its main forces are on 
the war fronts and the military is under surveillance he said 
past coup attempts failed for lack of resources and organization 
some observers suggest the eritreans could seize asmara any time 
they chose because they have popular support and most governemnt 
soldiers probably would quit fighting 
others believe an assault on asmara might panic the defenders 
into burning the elegant garden city once the capital of italys 
prized african colony 
i think theyd rather starve it into surrender one analyst 
said the commanders would probably fly out before the end and 
the city would be wide open 
a desire to starve rather than destroy asmara may lie behind the 
rebels refusal to reopen the nearby port of massawa some 
diplomats say 
massawa one of ethiopias two red sea ports has been idle 
since the rebels captured it in early february 
two months ago the united nations thought it had the agreement 
of both the government and rebels to send a damageinspection team 
to massawa 
at the last minute however the rebels refused entry to the 
ship carrying the team the eritreans have not explained the 
action but some analysts in addis ababa say the rebels may have 
feared any food delivered through massawa would primarily benefit 
mengistus beseiged 2nd army 
an estimated 400000 civilians live in asmara and the small 
surrounding area still held by the 2nd army a force of about 
120000 
food is supplied to the civilians by a un airlift from assab 
ethiopias other port far down the coast near somalia the 
government also flies in arms and food for the soldiers 
eritreans outside the besieged area are fed adequately if not 
abundantly by a relief effort run by the rebels from neighboring 
sudan 
the food is getting into asmara but its not enough and its 
not clear whether the army is laying claim to some of it said a 
european diplomat familiar with the un airlift which began july 
1 
mengistu responded to the economic crisis earlier this year by 
scrapping the marxist policies his government had followed for 15 
years and encouraging foreign investment many diplomats say it was 
too little too late and point to signs of increasing corruption 
and poverty 
as the economy deteriorates and the tigre peoples liberation 
front moves ever southward toward addis ababa residents of the 
capital are getting jittery 
in addition to the long lines at the immigration department 
about 100 people a day apply for visas at the us embassy those 
with money hoard food gasoline and water and the black market in 
foreign currencies is brisk 
</TEXT>
