<TEXT>
there are no violins or bright 
costumes in this ragtag gypsy settlement 30 miles from budapest 
just the memory of centuries of oppression and a skeptical view of 
the future 
four decades of communism did little to temper the bitter 
history of gypsies in eastern europe and the coming of democracy 
is not enough to inspire trust within the dirtfloored shacks of 
kerepestarcsa 
most inhabitants wear dirty handmedowns a 30yearold looks 
50 and few of the children wear shoes no one is sure how many 
people live here 
the average traveler thinks heres a gypsy hes happy well 
fed and plays wonderful music but that is only 1 percent of the 
gypsy population said bela osztoikan head of the gypsy 
organization phralipe or brotherhood 
in reality most of them live in poverty and where there is 
poverty there is no culture there is more crime and there is 
darkness 
leaders of eastern europes 6 million gypsies have no praise for 
the former communist regimes which were guilty of forced 
assimilation exploitation and discrimination and little faith in 
a democratic future 
most gypsies are afraid of change which takes them toward 
the unknown said manush romanov of bulgarias democratic union 
of roma one of the two main gypsy branches calls itself roma and 
the other is sinti 
however deep their distrust the new freedom allows gypsies to 
voice their frustrations openly for the first time in decades 
the communist hungarian leaders of the past 45 years stripped 
the gypsies of their own communities forbade them to practice the 
trades of their ancestors spoke disparagingly of their language 
and culture gypsy author jozsef choli daroczi said recently 
in hungary and elsewhere the communists preached equality in an 
attempt to paper over centuries of prejudice that culminated in the 
extermination of an estimated 500000 european gypsies by the nazis 
the hatreds did not die prominent in the budapest graffiti of 
the 1980s was oac for oeld a ciganyt which means kill the 
gypsy 
a 1983 song by the hungarian rock group mosoly contains the vow 
to exterminate all gypsies adults and children 
officials also did their part in czechoslovakia jozef prokop 
of the government commission for the problems of the gypsy 
populance said a few years ago that 20 percent of gypsy newborns 
were mentally retarded 
he expressed horror at a birth rate of 7000 a year in an 
estimated gypsy population of 600000 and advocated enforced birth 
control prokop also recommended alternative methods of raising 
gypsy children for example in foster homes special boarding 
schools and the like 
gypsies say bulgaria responded to a perceived danger of gypsy 
overpopulation with a 30year assimilation campaign that began in 
the 1950s and included forced name changes 
by the 1960s at the latest everything had been forbidden that 
had anything to do with gypsyhood romanov said he described 
attempts to destroy gypsy traditions and language as cultural and 
ethnic genocide 
less forced assimilation occurred in poland and romania but 
gypsies there were pressured into giving up traditional ways in the 
name of equality 
despite their numbers an estimated 3 million in romania alone 
gypsies became an ethnic nonentity and others made the decisions 
relating to them 
what special status they were given was negative in hungary 
television programs dealing with crime showed photographs of 
juvenile offenders only if they were gypsies 
after trying to erase the old traditions communist authorities 
across east europe offered no real way for gypsies to integrate 
and left them generally with poor schooling substandard housing 
and little medical care 
such neglect produced an army of gypsy school dropouts that 
became a source of cheap unskilled labor for stateowned 
enterprises 
gypsies now stand to suffer most from the double squeeze of 
companies closing or laying off thousands of employees and 
costconscious governments cutting back on social programs 
in a capitalist system there will be no further need for the 
great masses of the gypsy people qualified only for menial tasks 
phralipe said in its founding declaration last year they will be 
pushed to the edge of society 
beggars and black marketeers have reappeared in european 
capitals many are gypsies 
east europeans share the perception that much of the increase in 
crime is attributable to gypsies 
such developments have given new life to old beliefs that 
gypsies are thieves and loafers 
they are all accusing us of murderous crimes said a 
30yearold gypsy from giurgiu in southern romania 
antigypsy feeling has led to violence unthinkable under 
communist regimes where rowdies had more fear of police in 
prague czechoslovakia roving bands of skinheads have attacked 
gypsies 
weve had so many promises that were tired of them said 
ilona bango 30 joining companions in reciting a long list of 
wrongs let action replace words 
</TEXT>
