<DOCNO> AP900905-0184 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
when director fritz lang fled nazi germany in 
1933 he gazed out the dining car of his train and brushed the hair 
out of his eyes the wind sweeping across his face he then watched 
the tracks join together split in two and join together again 
at least thats how howard rodman imagines it he also imagines 
a meeting between lang and nazi propaganda chief joseph goebbels 
theyre sitting in goebbels office parallelograms of light 
shining on a dusty parquet floor as the propaganda minster speaks 
lang stares at a large municipal clock outside a ray of sunlight 
inching towards his shoe 
destiny express 1795 atheneum is rodmans first 
published novel the writing clean and welllighted it was 
inspired appropriately by one of langs movies during an 
afternoon in 1982 when rodman took time off from his job as a union 
organizer in manhattan and sat through the directors classic 
thriller the testament of dr mabuse 
rodman who always loved film noir of the 1940s and 50s said 
the lang film was one of those movies that changes your life 
part of it was realizing how much of contemporary films from 
star wars stuff to indiana jones come right out of this 
particular film he said part of it was the joy of watching 
somebody inventing the language of filmmaking right before your 
eyes how you tell a story through shots and narratives was 
something that he along with other people devised and i watched 
that happening 
lang was one of germanys most celebrated directors until the 
nazis came to power and rodman who had completed a novel about 
sex drugs and politics in new york tracked down his other 
films metropolis and m among them he also read books and 
contemporary reviews 
rodman considered an essay about langs films but instead was 
drawn to dramatizing the director especially the artistic 
collaboration with his wife thea von harbou who remained in 
germany and eventually became a nazi 
its pretty clear that their partnership was equal said 
rodman who has written for the magazines premiere and american 
film but the real kicker was how they each thought of those 
films 
he looked back at all the films he made prior to leaving 
germany as the films that of course were the films that someone 
when confronted with nazism would have to be repelled by it would 
have to escape it would leave behind your career your language 
everything 
she saw the exact same films as the absolute natural 
precursors of what the nazi party was doing she saw metropolis 
as leading everything inevitably and joyfully to the ascension to 
power of hitler i wanted to know how two people could be so 
incredibly intimate as collaborators and yet have widely different 
world views 
destiny express named after langs 1921 film destiny 
takes place during the directors last days in germany thea is 
having an affair with an american surrealist fellow artists 
bertolt brecht billy wilder and max ophuls are leaving the 
country and goebbels has offered lang the chance to make 
propaganda films 
this is rodmans equivalent to motivational light a novel so 
visual that shadows seem to streak across the page and the words 
stand out like individual frames 
alone in the corrider he scraped a wood match against the 
wall lighting a cigarette rodman writes 
langs feet like his hands were quite large and he walked 
with an erect military carriage he had been out here for most of 
the film extinguishing coarse imported cigarettes on the floor 
and watching the play of his distinctly multiple shadows the 
shadows elongated and foreshortened as he paced the hallway 
lang adjusted his monocle and idly lit one more match 
i didnt know what the characters faces would look like or 
what they were going to say unless i knew what the light was in the 
room rodman said im not in real life usually a glum sort of 
custard but i wanted that sense of the world closing in 
i think it is true that what lang is thinking is a world in 
which the camera the car the airplane all are used for 
purposes for genocide and not longer after the events of this 
book 
adapting destiny express to film seemed obvious and rodmans 
agent is working on a deal in which the movie would be shot in 
europe using englishspeaking actors all rodman had to do was 
prepare a treatment a process painful enough to give him 
nightmares about parallelograms of light 
it was the hardest thing i ever had to write he said i 
had to turn the book inside out in order to do it find some 
external equivalent for every literary thing in this book the 
writing was deceptively cinematic you had to reinvent it from the 
details i did it but i never will again 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

