<TEXT>
this western wisconsin community in 
many ways the center of the dairy industry is the first 
battleground over proposed changes in the governments decadesold 
milk pricing system 
it hosts the first hearing today in a rare us department of 
agriculture investigation into whether the federal milk marketing 
system should be altered to eliminate price disparities from one 
region to another 
the formula partially pays farmers based on how far they live 
from eau claire a city of about 50000 located 120 miles east of 
minneapolis in the heart of wisconsins dairy farm region 
dairy farmers close to eau claire argue the milkpricing system 
is unfair outdated and provides artificially high subsidies for 
producers in the south and west who live farthest from here 
the milk marketing order system created in the 1930s is 
designed to insure an adequate supply of milk move milk from 
highproduction areas and stabilize the market said bob cropp a 
dairy marketing specialist at the university of wisconsinmadison 
but while milk production in the south and west traditionally 
nondairy producing states that have received higher prices for 
their milk has increased markedly the current system continues 
to pay farmers in those regions more than the midwest cropp said 
i dont mind competing against farmers from the south and west 
as long as we are competing by the same rules said wisconsin 
dairy farmer pete knigge the chairman of the national commission 
on agriculture and rural development policy 
officials expect the hearings to manifest the strong regional 
splits over the issue 
certainly there is a great divergence of opinion among 
producers in various parts of the country on changes needed in the 
order program said jim barr chief executive officer of the 
national milk producers federation in virginia 
the federation represents about 100000 dairy farmers who 
produce 70 percent of the nations milk barr said the groups 
membership is about evenly split over whether the current system 
should be changed he said 
an administrative law judge will conduct the agriculture 
department hearings which will explore about 60 different 
proposals to alter the system us rep steven gunderson rwis 
said 
the administrative law judge will make recommendations to us 
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter who observers predict will 
take two to three years to institute changes 
three days of testimony are planned in eau claire the remaining 
hearings will be sept 1019 in minneapolis sept 20 in st cloud 
minn oct 15 in syracuse ny oct 1012 in tallahassee fla 
and oct 15 in dallas 
the present system includes a transportation factor in 
determining what farmers are paid for milk the farther a farmer 
lives from eau claire the more the producer receives 
while wisconsin remains the no 1 milk producing state with 
about 175 percent of the nations milk supply a title it has 
held for the last century california has moved into second place 
with a 13percent share of the market 
eau claire became the measuring spot for the transportation 
differential in 1961 because the bulk of us was produced in 
wisconsin and minnesota and eau claire was center of that 
production 
when you look at the kind of increases in production in the 
south and west there simply is no rhyme or reason for providing 
incentives based on how far you live away from eau claire 
gunderson said 
for example in june a wisconsin dairy farmer on the average 
earned 1420 for every eight gallons of milk he produced based on 
the federal milk orders barr said 
the same farmer in florida got 1730 
