<TEXT>
its getting a little easier to get into one of 
businesss more exclusive clubs 
two new york stock exchange seats in the past two months have 
each sold for 301000 each the lowest level in more than 5 years 
prices of seats which entitle members to trade directly on the 
stock exchange floor tend to reflect the level of trading volume 
on the nyse the nations largest stock exchange 
the latest sale on tuesday matched the price paid on aug 23 
continues a decline that has driven down prices from the alltime 
high of 115 million in september 1987 a month before the stock 
market crashed 
a seat last sold for 300000 on dec 17 1984 
brokerage firms in the last year have reduced personnel and 
operations individual investors have shied away from stocks and 
commission rates have fallen reducing the desirability of owning 
a seat less trading means lower commissions and less revenue for 
brokerage firms 
the price of an nyse membership has fallen steadily since the 
1987 market crash after a steady rise that took seats from a low of 
35000 in 1977 to 105000 in 1978 425000 in 1983 and 600000 
in 1986 
the high seat price this year was 430000 on june 7 according 
to stock exchange records there have been 24 seat sales so far in 
1990 including seven in august compared with 26 in all of 1989 
the most recent seat sales have been 370000 on july 17 
330000 on aug 3 325000 on aug 14 320000 on aug 15 
310000 on aug 20 301000 on aug 23 309000 on aug 28 and 
