<TEXT>
troubled loans for real estate and leveraged 
buyouts are adding to the burdens of the nations biggest banks 
moodys investors service inc said 
the problems are hindering the banks recoveries from past 
mistakes in lending to developing nations the credit rating agency 
said 
in a pessimistic annual review moodys said tuesday the 1990s 
may be the decade in which some powerful regional institutions 
challenge the supremacy of the nationwide moneycenter banks 
while the creditworthiness of most of the nine moneycenter 
banks has steadily declined since the 1970s problems have 
accelerated in recent years with credit rating reductions 
moodys said in a 37page report that major trouble spots for 
banks are 55 billion in commercial real estate loans inadequate 
reserves to cover nonperforming loans to developing countries and a 
large exposure to buyouts and other highrisk transactions 
the nine money center banks are bankamerica corp bankers trust 
new york corp chase manhattan corp chemical bank corp 
citicorp continental bank corp first chicago corp 
manufacturers hanover corp and jp morgan amp co 
the report said that all the money centers except jp morgan 
and bankers trust are undercapitalized because of the sharp 
deterioration in domestic asset quality and low domestic reserves 
moodys said it was not clear the banks could rebuild capital 
quickly enough to absorb additional provisions against domestic and 
developing country loans which might be required 
the report mentioned security pacific corp of los angeles 
wells fargo amp co of san francisco ncnb corp of charlotte nc 
and banc one corp of columbus ohio as key superregionals for 
the 1990s 
the most recent round of creditrating downgrades affecting 
citicorp and other giants were prompted by the real estate slump 
and moodys offered no promises that further downgrades could be 
avoided 
moodys said vacancy rates remain high in big cities which 
appear to be overbuilt and that construction loans of all types 
are potentially troublesome particularly for hotels and strip 
shopping centers 
market psychology has deteriorated as the savings and loan 
scandal has forced many regional and moneycenter banks to reduce 
new real estate lending that has put developers under pressure and 
made existing properties tough to sell moodys said 
the credit agency listed texas arizona new england oklahoma 
tennessee and colorado as highly distressed markets it said 
significant risk elements exist in new jersey georgia 
maryland virginia pennsylvania california new york and florida 
chemical bank had the largest percentage of nonperforming 
commercial real estate loans on which no interest is being paid 
at 155 percent followed by citicorp at 139 percent and first 
chicago at 126 percent jp morgan had by far the lowest rate 
04 percent 
overall 114 percent of the banks 549 billion in commercial 
real estate loans outstanding in march were described as 
nonperforming the report said 
moodys also said banks still need to increase their reserves 
to account for a larger slice of outstanding loans to latin 
american countries 
moodys said average coverage by banks increased to 50 percent 
in the first quarter of 1990 from 37 percent in 1988 but the level 
remains below the 75 percent to 100 percent established by most 
regional and international banks 
further clouding the future of national banks is exposure to 
highrisk transactions mostly leveraged buyouts initiated in the 
mid to late 1980s in a leveraged buyout an investor or investors 
borrow a large amount of money to purchase a corporation and then 
sell assets to make interest payments 
moodys said the nations moneycenter banks had 54 billion in 
exposure to highly leveraged transaction at the end of 1989 up 
from 32 billion in 1988 in part because of a broader regulatory 
definition 
but the report pegged hlt exposure as a major coming problem 
area with nonperforming assets expected to rise substantially 
compounding the problems is the collapse of the junk bond market 
which was envisioned as a place to refinance some leveraged buyouts 
problem borrowers may go bankrupt resulting in a lengthy 
workout process before the banks can recover their principal 
moodys said 
in several instances asset sales have fetched prices below 
expectations the report said as a consequence those lbo 
structures that rely upon asset sales or refinancing to meet 
maturing principal may encounter difficulty in the next few 
years 
