<TEXT>
the international monetary fund which has 
prescribed financial austerity and freemarket capitalism for 
countries from mexico to mozambique may be about to issue the same 
prescription to the capital of world communism 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said tuesday that an 
imfled study of the soviet economy will be on the agenda when 
president bush meets with soviet president mikhail gorbachev in 
helsinki finland on sunday 
industrialized nations meeting at the economic summit in houston 
in july ordered the imf and three other international financial 
institutions to study the soviet unions needs and the 
opportunities for western help 
president bush will be interested in the progress that has 
been made in that assessment and president gorbachevs views of 
the reform effort fitzwater said 
the imf founded in a new hampshire village 46 years ago to 
stabilize the exchange of money among nations is coordinating the 
study also taking part are the washingtonbased world bank which 
makes loans for projects in third world countries the parisbased 
organization for economic cooperation and development and the 
newly formed european bank for reconstruction and development 
graham newman deputy chief of the imf information office said 
a team representing the four organizations has been in the soviet 
union conducting interviews and collecting data for the study 
which is due to be completed by the end of the year 
newman said the imf will not have a representative in helsinki 
but it could well be that the team will submit to the president 
a memo on its progress 
of the four agencies the imf is perhaps the most controversial 
partly because of policies that its critics say have imposed 
stringent economic rules on developing nations to the detriment of 
the poor 
the standard prescription for countries suffering from 
inflation to get an imf loan is dismissal of workers from public 
employment deflation of the currency and removal of subsidies on 
basic staples said laurence birns president of the council on 
hemispheric affairs there is no question that the group that 
bears the heaviest burden in these restructuring efforts are the 
poor and the rural middle class 
imf spokesman newman conceded that in any economy when 
adjustments need to be made there are some shortterm problems 
but newman said the fund encourages the countries to develop a 
safety net to protect the most disadvantaged 
i suppose one has to look at the alternatives newman said 
if countries do not put their economies back in order again 
things are only going to go from bad to worse and the poor are 
going to suffer even more 
in addition to barbs from liberals such as birns and his group 
the imf has faced opposition from economic conservatives 
i think the problem is that they have essentially become a 
dole said doug bandow a senior fellow at the cato institute 
we have seen throughout latin america that as a practical matter 
countries will get money year after year even if they dont live up 
to their conditions 
newman took issue saying if performance criteria have not 
been attained and a country wants to continue with the program 
that triggers an automatic consultation to find out what went wrong 
and why it went wrong he said imf loans have been stopped in 
many many cases 
bandow also argued that imf conditions encourage countries to 
adopt protectionist measures which hurt their economies and to 
raise taxes rather than reduce spending to curb budget deficits 
my guess is that the study of the soviet economy may not be 
a bad thing bandow said the problem is that the policy of the 
imf suggests that whatever the study is the outcome isnt going to 
be terribly helpful 
the fivemonth deadline for the soviet study came as a shock to 
some in organizations accustomed to more leisurely studies 
we did a study of the chinese economy many years ago said 
peter riddleberger press manager for the world bank it took 
several years of course 
