<TEXT>
a handful of major japanese banks may face a 
downgrading in their credit ratings following the recent dramatic 
fall in the tokyo stock market and amid pressure to improve their 
profitability an international credit rating agency said wednesday 
among the banks put on rating watch by the ratings agency 
ibca are the socalled big five city banks daiichi kangyo bank 
fuji bank mitsubishi bank sanwa bank and sumitomo bank and the 
industrial bank of japan 
these institutions currently carry a aaa rating the highest 
credit rating available 
but ibca noted that their results in recent years have been 
increasingly dominated by the stock market which has declined 
sharply this year that decline coupled with the weakness of the 
japanese yen have brought to an end the virtuous circle whereby 
japanese banks could finance at insignificant costs virtually any 
level of growth the agencys report said 
ibca predicted life for japanese banks is going to be more 
difficult for here on 
the bigfive banks have increased their equity base by more than 
300 percent over the past five years or roughly 40 billion the 
agency said but those gains were possible because japanese 
investors have been willing to put up with minimal dividends 
ibca said oncepliant investors may go on strike as capital 
losses mount 
further ibca noted that japanese banks have been slower than 
their international peers in setting aside reserves to cover 
problem foreign loans and those losses are expected to mount 
but the agency said its overall concerns center on high monetary 
growth and the current international tensions rather than the 
performance of individual banks 
ibca said that other japanese banks also may be put on a ratings 
watch 
