jury selection began today in what promised to be 
a lengthy and complicated trial of 14 currency traders charged in a 
wideranging probe of corruption in the citys commodities pits 
the defendants all traders of japanese yen futures contracts 
face 393 counts stemming from allegedly illegal trading practices 
at the chicago mercantile exchange 
jury selection began before us district court judge william t 
hart said a clerk in harts chambers who declined to be identified 
by name 
hart has set opening statements for next tuesday in the trial 
which is expected to last four months 
a 15th defendant martin riley jr pleaded no contest during 
pretrial motions tuesday to one count of mail fraud and two counts 
of violating the commodities exchange act said assistant us 
attorney dan gillogly riley a trader in the japanese yen pit 
listed financial and health reasons when entering the plea 
hart accepted the plea conditionally until he reviewed rileys 
financial and health records gillogly said 
the trial is the second major trial stemming from an undercover 
fbi investigation at the merc and the chicago board of trade 
the 14 defendants are accused of violating the commodities 
exchange act by executing trades outside the openoutcry system at 
the futures exchanges 
in all 48 people have been indicted in the probe fbi agents 
posed as traders and secretly tape recorded conversations that 
prosecutors said revealed fraud among traders at the merc and the 
cbot 
in the first trial a federal jury convicted two swiss franc 
traders on relatively minor trading violations a third trader was 
acquitted 
the jury in that trial failed to reach verdicts on scores of 
more serious charges including a racketeering count against one of 
the defendants and mail and wirefraud charges against all three 
the scandal prompted the merc the cbot and their regulators to 
adopt tougher antifraud measures and congress is considering 
regulatory changes to strengthen the markets integrity 
yen trader aric march pleaded guilty aug 24 to two counts of 
mail and commodities fraud as part of a plea agreement the 
government agreed to drop fraud charges against him according to 
court documents the government had accused march of prearranging 
trades of sampp 500 futures with another broker 
march is expected to testify in the other yen traders trial 
six of those traders are charged with racketeering conspiracy 
and all are charged with wire and commodities fraud 
the trial of 12 cbot soybean futures traders is scheduled to 
begin monday before us district judge george marovich 
one soybean trader who was to go on trial before marovich 
pleaded guilty in late august to racketeering and tax fraud the 
trader james d nowak was charged last year with two counts of 
racketeering more than 200 counts of fraud and violations of the 
commodity exchange act 
