<TEXT>
the united states wants its allies to 
pay the entire cost of its military buildup in the persian gulf an 
estimated 1 billion a month senior administration officials said 
wednesday 
the officials provided some of the first specific figures on 
what president bush had in mind when he called last week for 
americas allies to pay their fair share of the campaign against 
iraqi president saddam hussein 
bush directed two of his closest cabinet aides secretary of 
state james a baker iii and treasury secretary nicholas brady on 
global fundraising missions 
baker was scheduled to tour the oilrich capitals of the middle 
east while brady was in the middle of a whirlwind tour of four 
capitals in four days 
after meetings with french officials and british prime minister 
margaret thatcher bradys delegation made a refueling stop in 
anchorage before flying on to meetings friday with south korean 
president roh taewoo and japanese prime minister toshiki kaifu 
in london baker pronounced mrs thatcher enormously 
supportive aides said she promised detailed figures soon 
the secretary also said his french visit was a success 
the senior administration officials briefing reporters on 
condition that they not be named said that bradys mission was 
focusing on two types of assistance 
one is emergency aid for countries especially hard hit by the 
trade embargo against iraq and the other is cash and contributions 
to defray the costs incurred by the united states in its big 
buildup of troops and ships in saudi arabia and the persian gulf 
the officials put the total cost of the buildup at 6 billion 
through the end of 1990 and estimated it would average 1 billion a 
month after that 
a request to allies to meet the entire us cost is reasonable 
one official said because they couldnt buy this military 
capability anywhere else in the world 
the officials indicated that the administration hoped for many 
contributions such as oil air and sea transportation and medical 
supplies in part to blunt the criticism that cash donations 
effectively turn the us military into a mercenary force 
one official said the worldwide search for donations was linked 
in part to the us budget deficit 
brady told reporters traveling aboard his plane wednesday that 
the administration remained opposed to any efforts to reduce the 
targets for deficit reduction next year 
he said the president strongly favored reducing the deficit 
projected at 231 billion for the 12 months beginning oct 1 by 
50 billion next year and reducing cumulative deficits by 500 
billion over five years 
egypt jordan and turkey would be the principal candidates for 
trade asssistance estimated as needing 35 billion through the 
end of this year and another 7 billion next year 
the officials said that the conversations with thatcher and the 
french centered primarily on this issue and involved a dicusssion 
of a possible 3 billion in aid that the 12nation european 
community was scheduled to take up friday at a meeting of european 
finance ministers in rome 
in addition to aid to the socalled front line states of egypt 
turkey and jordan and the military payments to the united states 
the administration also wants to raise an unspecified amount to be 
used to alleviate economic damage from rising oil prices in 
countries such as the philippines brazil and the emerging 
democracies of eastern europe 
the officials would not discuss an overall price tag but the 
various elements could well add up to more than 25 billion 
the paris and london stopovers were seen as a way for the united 
states to gain endorsements for bushs call for burdensharing 
before the administration solicits japan and west germany two 
economic superpowers who have been accused especially by many 
members of congress of not doing enough so far in the persian gulf 
crisis 
the officials on bradys plane said that japans pledge of 1 
billion in aid was a good beginning but they did not dispute 
reports that the administration will press for more 
one officials said that taiwan a country that is not on the 
travel agenda of either brady or baker would be approached by a 
thirdparty emissary and asked for support because of diplomatic 
relations with mainland china the united states is limited in the 
types of official contact it can have with taiwan 
before leaving london brady rejected a suggestion that foreign 
leaders might resent being leaned on by the united states for 
economic help 
quite the contrary mrs thatcher thought it was exactly the 
right thing to do brady said 
