<TEXT>
a federal judge wednesday refused to stop home 
box office inc from showing films containing songs copyrighted by 
broadcast music inc in a licensing dispute involving nearly all 
of hbos programming schedule 
but us district judge john sprizzo ordered hbo to pay bmi an 
interim fee for broadcasting films containing songs by bmi 
composers bmi sued hbo in january as hbos license was about to 
expire and the two sides couldnt agree on a new fee 
the broad licensing dispute which involves several lawsuits 
focuses on who and how much should be paid to music syndicates for 
the songs heard during movies 
sprizzo refused to slap an injunction on hbo that would have 
prevented the paytelevision service from showing about 80 movies 
on its september schedule that contain bmi songs including 
batman 
since its license expired jan 1 hbo has continued to broadcast 
such films without paying a fee 
we would have no schedule without bmi music hbo general 
counsel john redpath jr said and without a schedule we dont 
have a business 
bmi attorney robert sisk could not be reached for comment 
the lawsuit was filed amid efforts by bmi to boost its cable 
television levies beyond raising basic rates bmi wants to collect 
from local cable systems as well as from cable programmers it now 
charges just programmers that aspect of the case still is in 
litigation redpath said 
bmi represents more than 100000 composers and publishers of 
more than 15 million songs collecting a contracted fee whenever 
one of its songs is played it licenses radio and television 
stations hotel and restaurant chains even discotheques 
hbo owned by time warner inc has more than 23 million 
subscribers making it the largest paytelevision service in the 
nation 
redpath said hbo has paid for music rights for more than a 
decade and was willing to negotiate a new fee he said sprizzo 
suggested hbo pay bmi 15 cents per subscriber which redpath called 
too high redpath said the two sides would negotiate 
hbos fees amounted to about 27 cents per subscriber to bmi and 
the american society of composers authors and publishers which 
has about 45000 members 
bmi demanded a split license from hbo in which the cable service 
would buy performance rights for programs only until they are 
transmitted to the local oeprator the operator which transmits to 
the home viewer would have to negotiate licenses separately 
bmi has named manhattan cable television inc a local operator 
and a unit of time warner in the same lawsuit hbo contends that 
split licenses violate antitrust laws and says local operators 
with dozens of channels would be hardpressed to negotiate 
individual licenses for each program 
bmi lawyers have maintained that hbo has not proven that 
operators cannot negotiate individual licenses 
</TEXT>
