<TEXT>
the chicago mercantile exchange said wednesday it 
wants to tighten up the socalled circuit breakers in its 
stockindex futures market in a further attempt to prevent a 
runaway stockmarket collapse 
the merc said it had applied to the commodity futures trading 
commission to reduce the maximum daily price limit for standard amp 
poors 500 index futures to 20 points from 30 points 
the new limit would be equivalent to about 150 points on the dow 
jones industrial average the current limit of 30 points is equal 
to more than 250 dow points 
the mercs board of governors approved the lower limit after 
studying the workings of circuit breakers during recent periods of 
extreme market volatility that occurred during the week after iraq 
invaded kuwait in early august 
on the whole the circuit breakers have been given high marks 
and have been cited as having a stabilizing effect on the market 
the exchange said in a statement 
after consultations with futures and securities industry 
market participants the board concluded it would be beneficial to 
further reduce the maximum daily price limit for sampp futures the 
merc said 
sampp 500 futures are the most widely traded stockindex futures 
which are contracts to buy and sell baskets of stocks the 
contracts enable investors to hedge against stockmarket losses or 
speculate on stock prices without actually owning stocks 
some critics contend computerdriven trading strategies 
involving huge blocks of stocks and futures can cause violent price 
swings in the stock market limits on the price movement of the 
futures contracts are intended to act as brakes on a runaway stock 
market 
</TEXT>
